   <text>
      <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_ Princeton_1800-01_page01.jpg"/>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1800_01_27_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                  <date when="1800-01-27">27 <choice><orig>Jan.<hi rend="superscript">y</hi></orig><reg>January</reg></choice> 1800.</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  Dear Sir,
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               I have just received yours<lb/>
               of the 20<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. <choice>
                  <orig>inst.</orig>
                  <reg>instant</reg>
               </choice> - I am sorry<lb/>
               that the <unclear>dotting</unclear> goes on so slowly<lb/>
               - my having followed this <choice>
                  <orig>parsi<lb/>
               -monious</orig>
                  <reg>parsimonious</reg>
               </choice> plan has cost us both<lb/>
               much trouble - At <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Bristol_ENK">Bristol</placeName> it<lb/>
               plagued me more than I chose<lb/>
               to complain of -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I know that I could have all<lb/>
               the types that are immediately<lb/>
               wanting for £5 &amp; I<lb/>
               think if I can find a moments<lb/>
               <unclear></unclear> me next week when I go<lb/>
               to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName> to attend <unclear>Cast<hi rend="superscript">l</hi>
               </unclear> that<lb/>
               I can have them cast &amp; sent<lb/>
               to you to print <title ref="./Workography.xml#Early1">Harry &amp; Lucy<lb/>
               &amp; Frank</title>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Observe - Take Notice - NB -<lb/>
               <figure>
                  <figDesc>Pen-drawn illustration of a manicule stressing the next words.</figDesc>
               </figure>I never said that I thought<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1800_01_27_page02.jpg"/>

               Papas &amp; Mamas would be at<lb/>
               the trouble to learn to teach I <choice>
                  <orig>al-<lb/>
               ways</orig>
                  <reg>always</reg>
               </choice> feared they would not &amp;<lb/>
               therefore I refused to be paid for<lb/>
               the Book till it had actually<lb/>
               succeeded - But I did &amp; do say<lb/>
               that it is an excellent <choice>
                  <orig>improve<lb/>
               -ment</orig>
                  <reg>improvement</reg>
               </choice> in the art of teaching to read<lb/>
               though I say it that <choice>
                  <orig>sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>should</reg>
               </choice> not say it.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I feel so many qualms about<lb/>
               mixing new &amp; old in the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Paren1">Parents<lb/>
               Assistant</title> that I must beg - nay<lb/>
               <add>without any mixing of new</add>
               <lb/>
               insist that all the old <unclear>may</unclear>
               <lb/>
               finish in the month for March<lb/>
               <add>if you can put them all in March -</add>
               <lb/>
               <add>or in two volumes if they will fill them</add>
               <lb/>
               if <title ref="./Workography.xml#Barri1">the Barring out</title> is thrown<lb/>
               aside we dont care - but we are<lb/>
               convinced that the Publick will<lb/>
               be better pleased to have a<lb/>
               new series<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Moral1">Moral Tales</title> being a new series<lb/>
               of the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Paren1">Parents Assistant</title>
               <lb/>
               by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss E &amp;c.</persName> —<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>She has lately written two or<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1800_01_27_page03.jpg"/>

               three beautiful things - some of<lb/>
               them dramatic for <del>Children</del>
               <add>young people</add>
               <lb/>
               One that I almost prefer to<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#LazyL1">Lazy Lawrence</title> - If you are<lb/>
               good, &amp; tractable about the arrange<lb/>
               -ment abovementioned you shall<lb/>
               have them!!! —<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I understand that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> is to<lb/>
               offer you a translation of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BerqA1">Berquins</persName>
               <lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Bibli1"><choice><orig>Bibliotheque de village</orig><reg>Bibliotheque de villages</reg></choice>
               </title> — the<lb/>
               original is excellent &amp; I know that<lb/>
               the translators are fully equal to a<lb/>
               far more arduous task —<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>When you write please to<lb/>
               make your clerk send an account<lb/>
               of the Books sent to us since we<lb/>
               left <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName> - for <add>all</add> your accounts have<lb/>
               not reached us &amp; we do not know<lb/>
               what Books we ought to have —<lb/>
               - <choice>
                  <orig>N<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>.</orig>
                  <reg>Number</reg>
               </choice> 3 of one of the sets of Anderson is<lb/>
               wanting - please to put it<lb/>
               in your memorandum book -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <del>Please to send us to M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DugdX1">Dugdale</persName> bookseller&gt;</del>
               <lb/>
               We <hi rend="underline">desire</hi> to have the <choice>
                  <orig>vol</orig>
                  <reg>volume</reg>
               </choice> of the<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Bibli2">Bibliotheque Brittanique
               </title> which<lb/>
               translates part of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Pract1">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Prac Ed</orig>
                     <reg>Practical Education</reg>
                  </choice>
               </title> — we<lb/>
               want to correct our stile by seeing<lb/>
               its crookedness reflected in another language<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer/>
            <postscript>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1800_01_27_page04.jpg"/>
               <p>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> wrote to us to say that he thought<lb/>
                  <hi rend="underline"><title ref="./Workography.xml#Rivul1">
                     Rivuletta</title></hi> should not be thrown away<lb/>
                  upon <title ref="./Workography.xml#Early1">
                     <hi rend="underline">Early Lessons</hi>
                  </title> that it should be kept<lb/>
                  for a new Edition of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Pract1">
                     <choice>
                        <orig>Prac Ed</orig>
                        <reg>Practical Education</reg>
                     </choice>
                  </title> - We agree with<lb/>
                  him in this opinion &amp; request you will<lb/>
                  take out of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Early1">
                     <hi rend="underline">Rosamond</hi>
                  </title> the few pages which<lb/>
                  <hi rend="underline">relate</hi> to it - they will leave no Hiatus —<lb/>
               </p>
               <p>We shall send for books in future by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DugdX1">Dugdale</persName>
                  <lb/>
               </p>
               <p>Copy to Johnson<lb/>
                     Jan<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> 28<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1800<lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
            <closer>
               <address>
                  <addrLine/>
                  <addrLine/>
                  <addrLine/>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
